{
  "assumptions": [
    "Traffic assumed ~<1k–5k monthly visitors (cost-first, mostly idle, handful of generations/day) — serverless-no-VPC is the correct budget rung",
    "No strict SLA stated — single-AZ single-region budget tier is appropriate",
    "LLM and embedding external API calls are out-of-scope for AWS sizing but their latency (~1–2 min) drives Lambda timeout config (max 15 min, sufficient)",
    "Operator review queue is low-volume; a simple DynamoDB status filter + a thin Lambda-backed admin API is sufficient (no separate service)",
    "Corpus vectors stored as a single JSON/binary blob in S3 or DynamoDB item; Lambda loads wholesale per invocation — no vector DB needed",
    "Embeddings backfill CLI runs locally or from a developer machine; not modeled as a production AWS service",
    "No authentication for public gallery; operator review queue gated by Cognito (simple user pool, one operator)",
    "Pricing table cached in DynamoDB, refreshed by a scheduled EventBridge rule + Lambda — not a separate service tier",
    "CloudFront + WAF covers both the SPA and the API origin for edge protection and rate limiting",
    "No compliance regime (PCI/HIPAA) implied by the brief",
    "Cost estimates are on-demand list prices for us-east-1, presented as ranges over assumed monthly volumes. They exclude the AWS Free Tier, Savings Plans, Reserved Instances, and negotiated discounts.",
    "Assumed traffic ~100k–1M requests/month, applied equally to all three tiers (tiers differ by robustness, not traffic). Set \"expected monthly visitors\" in intake to change it."
  ],
  "clarificationsUsed": [
    "Cost-first + scale-to-zero confirmed → serverless-no-VPC (rung 1) for all tiers",
    "In-process brute-force cosine ranking → no vector DB, corpus blob loaded by Lambda",
    "~1–2 min LLM latency → Lambda (15-min max timeout) fits; no always-on compute needed",
    "Operator review is a tiny gated path → same API Lambda + Cognito, not a separate service",
    "Read-heavy cacheable gallery → CloudFront caching is the primary read-scale mechanism across all tiers"
  ],
